PY  - 2019
DA  - 2019/03/01/
SN  - 1386-4181
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/j.finmar.2019.02.003
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1386418118301411
KW  - Trading volume
KW  - Inventory
KW  - Volatility
KW  - High-frequency trading
KW  - Price impact
KW  - Mean reversion
AB  - I develop a model in which traders receive a stream of private signals, and differ in their information processing speed. In equilibrium, the fast traders (FTs) quickly reveal a large fraction of their information. If a FT is averse to holding inventory, his optimal strategy changes considerably as his aversion crosses a threshold. He no longer takes long-term bets on the asset value, gets most of his profits in cash, and generates a “hot potato” effect: after trading on information, the FT quickly unloads part of his inventory to slower traders. The results match evidence about high-frequency traders.
ER  - 

